  "grammar": [
    {
      "id": "g-hoti",
      "title": "\u1f45\u03c4\u03b9 (hoti) Clauses: Indirect Statement",
      "explanation": "Greek often introduces indirect statements with the conjunction <strong>\u1f45\u03c4\u03b9</strong> (hoti, 'that'). This works like English 'that' after verbs of saying, thinking, or knowing. Example: '\u03bb\u03ad\u03b3\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03bd \u1f45\u03c4\u03b9 \u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2 \u03b5\u1f30\u03bc\u03b9 \u03bb\u03ad\u03b3\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd' = 'they say <em>that</em> I am clever at speaking.' The verb inside the \u1f45\u03c4\u03b9 clause keeps its original mood and tense.",
      "examples": [
        { "greek": "\u03bb\u03ad\u03b3\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03bd \u1f45\u03c4\u03b9 \u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2 \u03b5\u1f30\u03bc\u03b9 \u03bb\u03ad\u03b3\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd.", "english": "They say that I am clever at speaking." },
        { "greek": "\u03bf\u1f50\u03ba \u03bf\u1f36\u03b4\u03b1 \u1f45 \u03c4\u03b9 \u1f51\u03bc\u03b5\u1fd6\u03c2 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c0\u03cc\u03bd\u03b8\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5.", "english": "I do not know what you have experienced." }
      ],
      "tip": "When you see \u1f45\u03c4\u03b9, look for the verb of speech or thought that introduces it, and the statement that follows it."
    },
    {
      "id": "g-article",
      "title": "The Greek Article: \u1f41, \u1f21, \u03c4\u03cc",
      "explanation": "Greek has a definite article that changes for gender, number, and case, much like 'the' would if English declined it. Masculine: <strong>\u1f41</strong> (ho), Feminine: <strong>\u1f21</strong> (h\u0113), Neuter: <strong>\u03c4\u03cc</strong> (to). The article is far more important in Greek than in English \u2014 it can turn any word into a noun: \u03c4\u1f78 \u1f00\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03ad\u03c2 = 'the true (thing)' = 'the truth'. It also helps identify a word's case when endings are ambiguous.",
      "examples": [
        { "greek": "\u03bf\u1f31 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ae\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03b9 (masc. nom. pl.)", "english": "the accusers" },
        { "greek": "\u03c4\u1f74\u03bd \u1f00\u03bb\u03ae\u03b8\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd (fem. acc. sg.)", "english": "the truth" }
      ],
      "tip": "The article is your best friend for determining case and gender. If you see \u03c4\u03ae\u03bd or \u03c4\u03cc\u03bd, you know the following word is accusative."
    }
  ],

